Title : Mating design
Text : {{Orphan|date=January 2015}}

'''Mating design''' is a schematic [[Hybridisation (biology)|cross]] between the groups or [[strain (biology)|strain]]s of [[plant]]s are made in a [[plant breeding]] that is common in [[agriculture]] and [[biology|biological science]].<ref name="george">{{cite book|title=Principle of Plant Genetics and Breeding|year=2007|author=George Acquaah|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|location=United Kingdom|isbn=9781405136464|page=141}}</ref> The mating design in plant breeding has two main objectives: (1) to obtain information and understand the [[genetic code|genetic control]] of a trait or behavior that is observed, and (2) to get the base [[population]] for the development of plant [[cultivar]]s.<ref name="george"/>  [[Analysis of variance]] in [[offspring]] plants results from a mating design was used to evaluate the effects of [[additive genetic effects|additive genetic]], [[dominance (genetics)|dominant]] level, [[epistasis]] and [[heritability]] value equal to the value of genetic expectations.<ref name="Hallauer">{{cite book|author=Hallauer |display-authors=etal |title=Quantitative Genetics in Maize Breeding|publisher=Springer Science+Business Media, LCC|pages=34, 86, 104, 119, 134|location=New York |ISBN=9781441907660 | year=2010}}</ref>

